## ipconfig lab 

### Syntax: ipconfig
- screen presents Windows IP configuration
  | Ethernet adapter Ethernet | Header information for the network interface, stating the values below belong to an Ethernet Adapter named Ethernet |
  | Connection-Specific DNS Suffix | helps Windows resolve the IP address of a device on a network
  | Link-Local IPv6 Addres | IPv6 address automatically given to the Ethernet adapter for communication on local network segments | 
  | IPv4 Address | Ethernet adapter's unique identifier on a network, assigned to the computer by the router |
  | Subnet Mask | helps identify whether an IP address belongs to the native local network or to a remote network.
  | Default Gateway | IP address a device uses to connect to networks out of the native LAN. Often points to the router


### Syntax: ipconfig /all
- presents detailed configuration information along with the basic information presented in 'ipconfig'
  | Description | name/model of the network adapater |
  | Physical Address | adapter's MAC address |
  | DHCP Enabled | states that the device is set to automatically receive IP address, subnet mask and default gateway from the DHCP server |
  | Autoconfiguration Enabled | states that if DHCP fails, the OS will use APIPA(Automatic Private IP Addressing). Window will self-assign this 'local-only address' if DHCP fails |
  | Lease Obtained | date and time the DHCP client received the current IP address |
  | Lease Expires | date and time the IP addressed leased by the DHCP is scheduled to expire, unless renewed |
  | DHCP Server | IP address of the device that assigned the current IP addresses |
  | DHCPv6 IAID(Identity Association ID) | IPv6 identifier for the specific network adapter, when DHCPv6 is in use. |
  | DHCPv6 Client DUID | DHCPv6 unique identifier for a client device, used to obtain an IPv6 address from the DHCPv6 server |
  | DNS Servers | Servers a domain-joined device uses to translate host/domain names into IP addresses |
  | NetBIOS over Tcpip | Legacy compatible feature that allows NetBIOS naming/services to run over TCP/IP

### Syntax: ping example.com
- tells windows to send ICMP packets to 'example.com'(each test packet is 32 bytes of data)
- Windows resolves the domain name example.com into an IP address
- Windows sends (4) ICMP packets by default
- Windows receives (4) replies. (1) reply for each sent packet. Containing the following information:
  - reply from xx.xxx.xxx.xx(the remote host responded
  - bytes=32(the reply was (32) bytes)
  - time=78ms( the time from send to reply took (78) ms)
  - TTL(Time to Live)=52(value that limits how many network hops a packet can pass through)

- Ping statistics for xx.xxx.xxx.xx:
   - Packets: sent = 4, received = 4, Lost = 0 (0% loss)
     - shows summary of the Ping
       - Sent = 4(computer sent (4) ping packets)
       - Received = 4(all (4) ping packets came back)
       - Lost = 0(none were lost)
       - 0% loss(the connection worked perfectly during this test

Approximate round trip times in milli-seconds:
    Minimum = 78ms, Maximum = 78ms, Average = 78ms
    - timing summary
      - Minimum = 78ms(fastest reply)
      - Maximum = 78ms(slowest reply)
      - Average = 78ms(average reply time)

### Syntax: tracert(trace route)
- used along with a target name(either hostname or IP address). Traces the network route traversed to reach the target system.
- Windows resolves hostname to IP address
59 ms    32 ms    42 ms  ec2-3-248-240-3.eu-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com 
- will stop after (30) hops(if the packet never reaches the destination
- first visible hop replied
- Windows sent (3) probes with a TTL of 1
- replies took (59)ms, (32)ms and (42)ms
- hops (2 thru 8) did not send a reply back(before the timeout)
  - these routers may be configured to not send back TTL-expired ICMP messages

### Syntax: nslookup
- looks up host/domain name
- returns the IP address of the 'looked for host/domain name'

Server:  ip-10-0-0-2.eu-west-1.compute.internal
Address:  10.0.0.2

Non-authoritative answer:
Name:    example.com
Addresses:  2606:2800:21f:cb07:6820:80da:af6b:8b2c
          93.184.215.14 

| Server | DNS server used for lookup |
| Address | DNS server's IP address
| Non-Authoritive Answer | DNS server replied to the lookup, but the server is not the original source for that domain name |
| Name: | domain name that was looked up |
| Addresses | IPv4 and IPv6 address associated with the host/domain name | 

### Syntax: netstat (arguements -a, -n, -o, -b)
- displays current established connections

C:\>netstat

Active Connections

  Proto  Local Address          Foreign Address        State
  TCP    10.10.230.237:22       ip-10-11-81-126:53486  ESTABLISHED

- shows (1) active TCP connection
| TCP | this connection is using TCP protocol, shown in the 'Proto' column |
| Local Address | shows machine IP address and port number of the active session |
| Foreign Address | remote system IP/port that your system to which you are connected |

| netstat -a | displays ALL established connections and listening ports |
| netstat -b | shows the program associated with each listening port and established connection |
| netstat -o | reveals the process ID associated with the connection |
| netstat -n | uses a numerical form for addresses and port numbers |
| PID(Process ID) | unique number the OS assigns to the running processes, helps identify exact processes running on the system |

# Key Takeaways
- the common network commands reveal much information about how exactly the system is communicating within the network
- while this information does not in itself point to any diagnosis, the information does allow an experienced user to infer about the condition of their network




























